"Twelve mossy cells from 12 rats were reconstructed. Their somata were large and their proximal dendrites were thick (Figs 1, 2A and 3A). Somata close to the granule cell layer (Fig. 4) tended to be fusiform, whereas those farther from the granule cell layer tended to be multipolar. Thorny excrescences were on proximal dendrites (Fig. 1) and sometimes on the soma. Dendrites extended through the hilus and appeared to avoid entering the CA3 field or gran- ule cell layer. Material Used: "An axon arbor consisting of a delicate net-like arborization in the [dentate gyrus] GCL [granule cell layer] (Amaral, 1978; Ribak and Seress, 1983; Han et al., 1993) was recovered in only four cells or ~10% of the 41 cells with defined axonal domains (Fig. 1). ... Basket cells and axo-axonic cells are difficult to discern (Han et al., 1993), and we cannot be certain that all of these cells were basket cells rather than being a mix of basket cells and axo-axonic cells, and therefore these cells will be designated GCL cells. Axo-axonic cells, however, often have extensive axonal branching in the hilus as well as in the GCL (Han et al., 1993), favoring the interpretation that these GCL cells, which did not have extensive hilar axons, were indeed basket cells <%1035 %> <% 1036 %>. ... Eight cells had axons arborizing predominantly in the IML [inner molecular layer] <% 1027 %> <% 1009 %> (Figs. 2, 3)."
Location in reference: p3992, right mid; p3992, right bot
Interpretation: SG basket (incl. cck) : hilar/granular proj to SMi = 1:2 (4:8)

Material Used: "Six [dentate gyrus] cells had axons that seemed to arborize preferentially in the outer half of the ML and are referred to as OML [outer molecular layer] cells <% 1013 %> <% 1006 %>. ... Of the 41 stained axonal arborizations, 22 showed this pattern, and, of these, 17 had adequately stained somatodendritic morphology as well. Compared with the IML [inner molecular layer] and OML cells, the axonal arborization of these cells was not as dense and in many cases branches seemed to wander randomly over the entire thickness of the ML. In general, the axonal arborization was most concentrated in the ML directly overlying the soma, and in occasional cases the axon arborization extended widely in the transverse plane as well, occasionally nearly to the limits of the ML in both the suprapyramidal and infrapyramidal direction. Eleven of the TML [total molecular layer] cells also had axon branches entering the hilus [11 neurons did not have axons in the hilus] <% 1005 %>."
Location in reference: p3993, left top; p3993, left mid

"We recorded from 233 [dentate gyrus] neurons in the IML [inner molecular layer] and 64 granule cells <% 1001 %> in the superficial granule cell layer (GCL) in postnatal day 14 (P14)ÐP25 rat slices using standard whole-cell patch clamp methods. ... We often (72.5% of IML recordings) found fast-spiking neurons <% 1036 %> <% 1040 %> <% 1008 %> that discharged intermittently during 2-s-long depolarizing steps (data not shown). However, we also found a subpopulation of neurons (27.5% of IML cells) whose morphology and intrinsic physiology did not resemble fast-spiking interneurons."

Interpretation: Inner molecular layer inhibitory to excitatory cell ratio is 169:64 (ventral) = 2.6:1

Material Used: "A small population of GluR2-immunoreactive hilar neurons <% 1041 %> exhibited morphologic features of dentate granule cells, including a small (8- to 12-[micro]m diameter) round-to-oval soma and a thin rim of immunoreactive cytoplasm surrounding the nucleus. These cells are referred to as granule cell-like GluR2- immunoreactive neurons. Neurons of this type were rarely encountered in sections from control rats. Only 90 +/- 19 were observed per hippocampus. They were excluded from counts of both total hilar neurons and GluR2+ hilar neurons."

"The much larger population (referred to as GluR2+ neurons) exhibited morphologic features characteristic of mossy cells <% 1002 %> <% 1043 %>: namely, an ovoid soma comparable in diameter to that of CA3 pyramidal cells (30-40 [micro]m) with three or four primary dendrites emerging from it (Amaral, 1978; Ribak et al., 1985). The nucleus was surrounded by abundant intensely GluR2-immunoreactive cytoplasm. The hilus contained a total of 21,542 +/- 849 neurons of this type (range of 18,450-23,625; Fig. 5). They accounted for 57 +/- 2% of the total hilar neuron population."
Interpretation: Cell count of Hilar Mossy and Hilar Quad MC together equals 21542

Material Used:
"We next investigated the response properties of HICAP- [hilar commissural-associational pathway-related] and
HIPP-like [hilar perforant path-associated] <% 1013 %> cells to COM and MPP stimulation, respectively. The
axonal arborizations of HICAP-like cells were mainly confined
to the IML [inner molecular layer] (Fig. 3E, upper), whereas the arborizations of HIPP-like
cells extended from the MML [middle molecular layer] to the outer one-third of the
ML (Fig. 3F, upper). Notably, both COM- and MPP-evoked EPSC [excitatory postsynaptic current]
amplitudes in HICAP- and HIPP-like cells were significantly smaller
than in GCs [granule cells] during 10-Hz train photostimulation (Fig. 3E,F,
middle). Unlike HICAP- and HIPP-like cells, TML-like [total molecular layer] cells, as reported
previously [Soriano and Frotscher 1993; Mott et al. 1997;
Hosp et al. 2014; termed atypical HIPP cells in Liu et al. (2014)],
had their cell bodies located at the hilar-GCL border and projected their axons throughout the entire ML (Fig. 3G, upper). ... Table 2 Properties of EPSC [excitatory postsynaptic current] in DG [dentate gyrus] INs [interneurons]"
Interpretation: As per HCO these 10 cells comprise HIPP, and outer molecular layer cells based on morphology

"FIGURE 4. Quantitative summary of the dorsoventral difference in hippocampal cytoarchitecture. A: The bar graphs show the NDs [numerical densities] (x10^3/mm^3) of glutamatergic principal neurons in each region. The line charts show the ratios (%) of GABAergic to glutamatergic neuron density. B: The bar graphs show the absolute numbers of glutamatergic principal neurons contained in a 300-[micro]m-thick hypothetical transverse slice. The line charts show the ratios (%) of GABAergic neurons to glutamatergic cell numbers in each area. C,D: Schematic representation of the neuron numbers contained in 300-[micro]m-thick hippocampal slices (C, dorsal; D, ventral). The bold numbers in boxes represent the total numbers of glutamatergic principal neurons obtained from the current study. The italic numbers represent the calculated numbers of GABAergic neurons in the slice, and those in the parenthesis represent the relative ratios of GABAergic to pyramidal or granule cell numbers. For comparison, the total numbers of mossy cells are shown in plane numbers in boxes of the dentate hilus, which are estimated from our previous results (Fujise and Kosaka, 1999). The numbers of mossy cells are very small, and thus the ratios of GABAergic neurons to mossy cells are not calculated. The statistically significant dorsoventral differences are indicated. *P < 0.05 and **P < 0.01."

"The somata of PCs [pyramidal cells] <% 2000 %> <% 2004 %> (n=55) were located in stratum pyramidale. Their spiny dendrites and rarely branching axons occupied all CA3 layers (Fig. 1A). The somata of PV+BCs [parvalbumin-positive basket cells] <% 2043 %> and AACs [axo-axonic cells] <% 2028 %> were located in strata pyramidale, oriens and lucidum, with dendrites seen in all layers. The axonal arbor of PV+BCs was predominantly in stratum pyramidale (Fig. 1B). By contrast, the axon arbor of AACs was shifted towards the border of strata pyramidale and oriens, where the axon initial segment (AIS) of most PCs is located (Fig. 1D). ... From a total number of 33 PV+ interneuron-PC pairs, presynaptic interneurons were identified as PV+BCs (n = 15) if there was no association between the axons of biocytin labelled boutons and ankyrin G stained AISs (Fig. 1Ga). We classified cells as AACs (n = 18) when their boutons outlined the AISs (Fig. 1Gb). ... Axon collaterals of CCK+BCs [cholecystokinin-positive basket cells] <% 2044 %> (n=14) ramified mostly in stratum pyramidale, although some axon collaterals could also be found in strata oriens and lucidum (Fig. 1C). On the other hand, axon collaterals of CCK+DTIs [dendritic-region targeting interneuron] <% 2014 %> (n=8) ramified mainly in strata lucidum and radiatum (Fig. 1E)."
Location in reference: p3753, left top; p3753, left mid; p3753, left mid
Interpretation: Principal cells ca3 (ca3 pyr + ca3c pyr) = 55/110

Material Used: "Based on their axonal projection, CB1-expressing [cannabinoid receptor type 1] interneurons in CA3 could be divided into four main groups (Fig. 3). Axon collaterals of basket cells <% 2044 %> (BC, n = 38) were mostly present in the pyramidal cell layer and its vicinity (Fig. 4A). Mossy-fiber-associated cells <% 2036 %> <% 2035 %> (MFA cell, n = 32) had their axon clouds mainly in the stratum lucidum, and gave rise to some additional collaterals in the hilus. Axon arbors of dendritic-layer-innervating cells <% 2023 %> (DLI cell, n = 52) were observed prevalently in the stratum radiatum, but their axon branches could be occasionally traced into the stratum moleculare of the dentate gyrus. Perforant-path-associated cells <% 2008 %> (PPA cell, n = 11) projected their axons almost exclusively into the stratum lacunosum-moleculare. ... In general, BCs were sampled mainly within or near the stratum pyramidale, MFA cells in the stratum lucidum, DLI cells in the middle part of the stratum radiatum, while PPA cells were most often found at the border of strata radiatum and lacunosum-moleculare. ... In 15 out of 32 MFA cells, their axons were found to penetrate into the hilus. ... In 20 out of 52 DLI cells, axon collaterals were observed in the stratum moleculare of the dentate gyrus. The least variance in axon projection was noticed among PPA cells. In most of the cases, their axons were restricted to the stratum lacunosum moleculare ... In addition to these previously identified cell types (Lasztoczi et al., 2011), we found two interneurons with their axon clouds predominantly, albeit not exclusively located in the stratum oriens <% 2045 %> (82.4 and 37.1% of the total axon, respectively, Fig. 4E). A part of their axon collaterals penetrated into the strata pyramidale and lucidum."
Location in reference: p1510, right bot; p1511, left bot; p1511, right bot; p1512, left mid; p1512, left bot

In 15 out of 32 MFA cells, their axons were found to penetrate into the hilus. ... In 20 out of 52 DLI cells, axon collaterals were observed in the stratum moleculare of the dentate gyrus. The least variance in axon projection was noticed among PPA cells. In most of the cases, their axons were restricted to the stratum lacunosum moleculare ... In addition to these previously identified cell types (Lasztoczi et al., 2011), we found two interneurons with their axon clouds predominantly, albeit not exclusively located in the stratum oriens <% 2045 %> (82.4 and 37.1% of the total axon, respectively, Fig. 4E). A part of their axon collaterals penetrated into the strata pyramidale and lucidum."
Location in reference: p1510, right bot; p1511, left bot; p1511, right bot; p1512, left mid; p1512, left bot

Material Used:
"A fully reconstructed representative IN [interneuron] is shown in Fig.
3b. The soma is located in stratum lucidum with dendrites
spanning all sublayers of the CA3 area. The main axons run
parallel with mossy fibers in stratum lucidum, emitting many
collaterals in strata lucidum and pyramidale, with significant
projections to the hilus. INs with similar axodendritic arborizations
have been described (12, 20), and we will refer to them as
mossy fiber-associated INs (MFA INs). Sixteen of 18 INs tested
showed similar anatomical properties <% 2035 %>. The remaining two INs <% 2036 %>
had axon arbors predominantly in stratum pyramidale, with
similar somatodendritic morphology and hilar axonal projections
to those described above. These two cells may be categorized as
basket cells. We also found that seven of eight tested cells were
immunopositive for the neuropeptide CCK (Fig. 3a)."

The HRP-injected nonpyramidal cells located between the stratum radiatum and the stratum lanunosum-moleculare (type II cells) <% 4028 %> <% 4015 %> showed different physiological characteristics from fast-spiking cells in the stratum pyramidale. Material Used: "The first cell type was a vertically oriented [CA1 stratum oriens] interneuron (15 of 55 cells) <% 4055 %> (Fig. 4A), similar to those previously described by Lacaille and co-workers (Lacaille et al., 1987; Lacaille and Williams, 1990). ... The cell bodies of the second interneuron type (n = 36) <% 4069 %> <% 4089 %> <% 4087 %> resided in the superior zone of st. oriens. These cells possessed large cell bodies (20-70 [micro]m) that differed from the first type of intemeuron in that they were usually horizontally oriented, that is, parallel to the pyramidal cell layer. The thick varicose dendrites of this cell type were few and seldom branched. These dendrites coursed horizontally, often for several hundred micrometers within st. oriens and alveus, but never crossed into st. pyramidale or st. radiatum. These interneurons correspond to superior zone cells originally described by Ramon y Cajal (1968). We were able to characterize the axons of 14 of these cells. Surprisingly, the axons of these cells crossed st. pyramidale and ran through radiatum to st. lacunosum, where they formed a highly branching plexus, covering an area of several hundred micrometers within st. lacunosum. This morphology matches that of somatostatin-containing cells of st. oriens (Naus et al., 1988; Schwartzkroin et al., 1990; Baude et al., 1993). After passing into st. radiatum, the axons of some of these cells send a ÒrecurrentÓ axonal branch back across st. pyramidale and into st. oriens (see Fig. 4A). This recurrent branch formed only a minor part of the axon ramification."
Location in reference: p4437, right bot; p4439, left top

"The somata of the eight [CA1] postsynaptic interneurones
reported here were located in the superior zone of s. oriens
close to the O-A [oriens-alveus] border. Their sparsely spiny dendrites
branched horizontally along s. oriens and the alveus, but did
not extend as far as s. pyramidale. A single axon originated
from the cell body, crossed s. pyramidale and ran through
s. radiatum to s. lacunosum-moleculare, where it ramified
extensively. No collaterals were observed outside
s. lacunosum-moleculare, and the axon arborization and
apparent boutons were confined to s. lacunosum-moleculare
in seven of these interneurons. ... The axon illustrated in the adjacent drawing was
reconstructed from the two neighbouring sections. The axon
of the remaining postsynaptic interneurone (Fig. 5) densely
innervated s. lacunosum-moleculare but one collateral also
branched in s. oriens <% 4089 %> [7 neurons with no collateral in SO] <% 4069 %>."
Location in reference: p190, left mid; p190, right top

"Light microscopic analysis revealed four populations of [CA1] R-LM [radiatum-lacunosum moleculare] interneurons with distinct
axons: (1) basket cells <% 4079 %> (n = 4) with axons predominantly ramifying in the pyramidal cell
layer; (2) Schaffer collateral/commissural pathway-associated interneurons <% 4015 %> (n = 10)
stratifying in stratum radiatum and, to a lesser extent, stratum oriens; (3) perforant
pathway-associated interneurons (n = 6) innervating the perforant path termination zone in
stratum lacunosum-moleculare of the CA1 area as well as equivalent portions of the dentate
gyrus and subiculum; and (4) neurogliaform interneurons (n = 2) characterized by their
dense, compact axonal and dendritic arbour."

"Whole-cell recordings were obtained from 94 [CA1] interneurons with
somata located within stratum oriens. Complete axon fills were
observed in 75 interneurons that were used in the subsequent
morphological and physiological analyses. The photomicrographs
in Figure 1 illustrate the four major classes of interneuron that
were encountered in this study. These cells were classified based
on the stratum (pyramidale, lacunosum-moleculare, radiatum, or
oriens) that was most heavily innervated by the primary axon
(Fig. 1). Twelve interneurons (16%) displayed axonal arborizations
restricted, primarily, to the pyramidal cell body layer (stratum
pyramidale), and were thus classified as perisomatic cells <% 4036 %> <% 4078 %> <% 4079 %>
(Fig. 1A). These cells typically possessed two to eight large,
apically oriented dendrites that projected through stratum pyramidale
and terminated in stratum radiatum and/or stratum
lacunosum-moleculare (Fig. 1A, see Fig. 3). ... Seventeen neurons (23%) exhibited axons that arborized extensively within stratum lacunosum-moleculare <% 4069 %> <% 4089 %> (Fig. 1B, see Figs. 4,5)."
Location in reference: p86, right mid; p86, right mid

"Thick axons were followed back from [CA1] stratum lacunosum-moleculare to stratum oriens
in many cases, however only four of them could be unequivocally connected to its cell body. Three
cells showed typical morphology of O-LM cells <% 4069 %> (Fig. 2A).43,47,54,61 The somata and dendrites were located in stratum oriens. The axons emerged from a proximal dendrite (Figs 1D, 2A), as also seen in intracellularly filled O-LM cells,29,47 crossed stratum pyramidale and radiatum, and began to arborize with much thinner collaterals in stratum lacunosum-moleculare. ... The fourth cell <% 4068 %> showed some striking differences from the conventional O-LM type cells (Fig. 2B). First, one of the main axons was faintly labelled and disappeared in the alveus. Second, it had a more profuse axonal arborization both in stratum oriens and stratum radiatum, whereas the main axon ran directly towards the hippocampal fissure, although it was impossible to follow through due to the very dense somatostatin-positive axon staining."
Location in reference: p42, right top; p42, right mid

extent <% 4004 %> (Figs. 2A, 3B)."

"All neurons in the first electrophysiological category (n = 22) were observed to be stellate cells as originally described by Ramon y Cajal (1901-1902). Cell bodies were preferentially located in the superficial (toward the pia; n = 10) or middle (n = 9) third of layer II, with only three neurons located in the deepest third (Figs. 2A, 3, 6). The soma shape was ovoid or trapezoid, with elongation always oriented perpendicular to the pial surface (Fig. 6). Some cell bodies were circular (n = 3). The average somatic dimensions were 23.0 +/- 4.4 [micro]m (n = 22; range 16-30 [micro]m) by 12.9 +/- 2.2 (n = 22; range 10-16 [micro]m). ... None of the cells corresponding to the second electrophysiological category (n = 12) described above had a stellate morphology. Eleven of them had a pyramidal-like appearance, while the remaining neuron was classified as a horizontal tripolar cell."
Location in reference: p573, left mid; p575 right top
Interpretation: MEC LII-LIII Pyramidal-Multiform:LII-III Pyramidal-Tripolar in mec = 12:22

Material Used: "The most numerous group (n = 15) consisted of cells that had a large (329.9 +/- 29.3 [micro]m^2) polygonal body and whose most distinctive morphological feature was the presence of multiple thick primary dendrites (see Table 1) that fanned out from the soma mostly in the ascending and horizontal direction (Figs. 2A, 5A). These dendrites branched repeatedly, thus covering an area that approximated the shape of a semicircle with the base oriented parallel to layer II (Fig. 2A). Because of the fanning out of their dendrites, we refer to these cells as the ÒfanÓ cells <% 6005 %>. ... We also identified a third group of cells that included all those layer II neurons (n = 7) whose morphological characteristics did not correspond to the fan or pyramidal cell category. We refer to this group of cells as the ÒmultiformÓ cells <% 6082 %>."
Location in reference: p126, right mid; p128, left top
Interpretation: LI-II pyramidal fan in lec2:LII-III pyramidal tripolar in lec2= 15:7

Material Used: "All recorded neurons from layer III were identified morphologically as pyramidal cells <% 6095 %> <% 6092 %> <% 6017 %>. The neurons had a large soma (250 +/- 21.1 [micro]m^2), on average almost identical in size to that of the layer II pyramidal cells (Table 1), from which a characteristic thick (5.88 +/- 0.36 [micro]m) apical dendrite and a profuse basal dendritic arborization emerged. As in the neuron illustrated in Figure 11, in all cases the apical dendrite was found to bifurcate prior to entering or at the border with layer II and then typically to ramify very profusely over layers II and I. The basal dendritic arborization was typically very extensive, spreading over a large area of layer III and, frequently (n = 8), also extending well into layer V (Figs. 12, 13). ... We also identified a third group of cells that included all those layer II neurons (n = 7) whose morphological characteristics did not correspond to the fan or pyramidal cell category. We refer to this group of cells as the ÒmultiformÓ cells <% 6082 %>."
Location in reference: p130, right top; p128, left top
Interpretation: LIII-V Bipolar Pyramidal in layers 3&4 + LIII pyramidal stellate + LIII pyramidal all in lec:LII-III pyramidal tripolar in lec2 = 8:7

Material Used: "The first category of neuron (n = 38) has a pyramidal cell appearance (Fig. 1A). The second category consists of cells (n = 15) that, like the pyramidal cells, have a distinct apical dendrite but, unlike the pyramidal cells, have a basal dendritic plexus that extends predominantly and for long distances in the horizontal plane. These dendrites remain, for the most part, within the limits of layer V. We refer to this second category as horizontal cells (Fig. 1B)."

"The first category of neuron (n = 38) has a pyramidal cell appearance (Fig. 1A). "We observed two morphological types of neurons, horizontal and multipolar ones. Horizontal neurons have nonspiny dendrites that run largely parallel to the pial surface (Fig. 2A; N = 4; preweaned N = 3, postweaned N = 1), whereas the nonspiny to sparsely spiny dendrites of multipolar neurons distribute in various directions (Fig. 2A; N = 4; preweaned N = 3; postweaned N = 1) [n = 8] <% 6094 %>. ... SCs [stellate cells] in MEC [medial entorhinal cortex] are located throughout LII (Figs. 1, 7A,B; N = 53; preweaned N = 28, postweaned N = 25). They have two to 11 spiny primary dendrites leaving the somewhat rectangular or elongated soma primarily from the apex and from the side, and extending horizontally but also towards the pia, leading to an apical tuft with a diameter of around 600 [micro]m. The spiny basal dendrites travel within LII horizontally and towards deep layers, and the total basal tree has a diameter of around 200 [micro]m in the plane of the cell layers. The basal dendrites are shorter than the apical dendrites and the basal dendrites of only 51% of the neurons (N = 27) reach LIII <% 6082 %>, whereas the basal dendrites of the remaining 49% (N = 26) stay within LII."
Location in reference: p1279, right top; p1280, right mid
Interpretation:
LI-II Multipolar-Pyramidal in LI = 8,
LII-III Pyramidal-Tripolar in LII = 27

Both have a pyramidal shaped soma, but one has the apex facing the pia and the other one has a horizontally oriented soma. Both have multiple oblique and vertically oriented spiny apical dendrites, instead of just one main apical dendrite as described for pyramidal and oblique pyramidal neurons (Figs. 7A,B). Therefore, these neurons have a morphology in between that of pyramidal, oblique pyramidal, and SCs [stellate cells]. We observed the type that has an intermediate morphology between SC and pyramidal neurons both in slices from preweaned animals (N = 5), and from postweaned animals (N = 5), and the same is true for the type with an intermediate morphology between oblique pyramidal neurons and SCs <% 6019 %> (preweaned N = 4, postweaned N = 1)."
Location in reference: p1280 right bot; p1281, right top
Interpretation:
55% of 22 = 11 are LI-II Pyramidal-Fan,
LII Oblique Pyramidal = 5

Material Used: "We observed four morphological types of putative principal neurons in LII of LEC [lateral entorhinal cortex]. The first type, the pyramidal neuron, has a vertically oriented pyramidal shaped soma, one prominent apical spiny dendrite with a diameter of around 600 [micro]m at the level of the pia and a spiny basal dendritic tree that spreads within LII and occasionally in LIII (N = 2) <% 6082 %> with a diameter of around 200 [micro]m in the horizontal direction (Figs. 7A,B; N = 7; preweaned N = 3, postweaned N = 4). ... The second type is the oblique pyramidal neuron with a tilted to horizontally oriented pyramidal soma <% 6094 %> (Figs. 7A,B; N = 8; preweaned N = 5, postweaned N = 3). ... The third type is the fan neuron <% 6094 %> (Figs. 7A,B; N = 11; preweaned N = 6, postweaned N = 5), whose spiny apical dendritic tree fans out from the soma and reaches a diameter of up to 900 [micro]m at the pia."

Interpretation: LII-III Pyramidal-Tripolar in LII = 2; LI-II Multipolar-Pyramidal in LII + LI-II Pyramidal-Fan in LII = 8+11 = 20
